abstract: From The Gentleman's Magazine. Douglas, Earl of Morton, wore a hat. abstract: The instrument of blackmail is alleged to be the Department of Justice. The Minister in charge of that department found, it appears, that one of his  , who had been appointed " juge d instruction," or, as we should say, prosecuting officer, in connection with the affairs of the Southern railways, was pushing his  to a point that might disturb a large number of the members of the Chamber of Deputies, upon whose Parliamentary support the Ministry relied. Now, however conven ient it might be to know all the facts in  these legislators, and to hold the facts suspended over the legislators as a guarantee of their political support, it is plain that as soon as the facts were published 'by authority or made the ba sis of criminal procedures, the Ministry would lose its hold upon these legislators. Accordingly, the magistrate who was proceeding to unearth rascality without fear or favor found himself so obstructed and hampered by his chief, the Min ister of Justice, that he was forced to offer his resignation, and gave the reasons for it in a letter which has not yet been published. He was immediately succeeded, in defiance, it is said, of cus tom, if not of law, by an examiner who was supposed to be more amenable to     litical considerations.

abstract: Ivlr. [Chanter]'s first expedition was in the shallow waters of Lake Jipe, on a raft made of palm stems. His object was to get a shot at the hippos. As he left his African followers on the shore, they showed their appreciation by shouting these cheering words: " Loolt out Eor crocodiles! If mas ter dies, who ll pay us? " There were many hippos-" the surface oP the lake dotted here and there by spots, which soon re solved themselves into the black, boxlike heads of my game." The huge beasts seemed quite indifferent at the approach of the strange craft. A group of five hippos n^as approached to  1'a0 yards; then, with a snort, they faced the raft. The rafts men seemed to have lost  3Ir. Chanter to stake a retreat, but he urged the crew until within 100 yards, when lie fired at the nearest animal; he missed, and then all oP the hippos disappeared. 1~'hen the sun rose, he counted fifty hippos, and talc(ng a good sight at ti. nearest one, he fired, and knew the bullet had reached its mark. He fancied that he would bag that hippo. but it sank out oP sight.  Tr Cltan ler writes: "I had not 3 et learned that the brain of these animals is very small, and that the only fatal shot is under the ear." Then the hippos seemed to have crowded him, for they were decidedly too near for comfort. Next, " slowly but steadily.," 1\ir. Chanter felt that the frail raft was being lifted up. The boatmen yelled with terror. Evidently the hippo found he had made a mistake, and he left the bottom oP the raft. Ilr. Chanter had shot at three hippos and no dead animal was visible.  Anything more disagreeable and danger ous than a hunt for buffalo in its own cov ert can hardly be imagined. The brush is not more than ten feet high, and through this the animals have made runways in numerable-but the branches meet at a man s shoulders. These paths cross and Cem oss in a labyrinthian way. Get caught In one o: these paths of a charging buf falo, and there can be no escape. Into just such an ugly brush as this llr. Chanter en tered, and there was a charge of buffaloes, but they passed on, separating just at the place where stood . Chanter. Then the  follower said: " Ham del Allah "=' Praise be to God"-and our sportsman says lie " began to underst;tnd m hy buffalo shooting in the brush has been always considered unsafe."  Mr. [Theodore Roosevelt]'s latest hunting experiences, in 1S93 and 189f, are neatly told. Antelope, where they once abounded, not far from his ranch, are by no means as abm:dant as they were. The only increase in the region of the Little \Iissourt has been in the wolves. Blaclctail at e not, how ever, diminishing. TVhere twenty were killed a dozen years ago for every one whitetail, now their numbers are about the same. The prong horn is getting scarcer, and so is the buffalo.elk. As to his battery, Mr.=Roosevelt has always been singular in his adhesion to the `Virichester, and he uses a .45-90. As to penetration, perhaps more stress is laid on that than it actually de serves. " Shock is useless if it is gained at too ,great expense of penetration or ac curacy." You may get flatness of  tory, but IP you are not accurate there is little use in it. ~'e are rather conservative, and having been brought up in the school of the ancient small bore, with a long and solid bullet, and a fair charge of powder, :ye rather hang to that than to big bores, extra heavy powder, and hollow bullets. The l7 believes more in a double-barreled rifle.  T'e put our faith in a repeating arm. " Each type has some good qualities' that the other lacks, and each has some defects." Then 1\Ir. Theo dore Roosevelt takes pleasure in noting what is Ilr. Selous's favorite arm. It is a rifle close to the type of that used by, us twenty-five years ago, of .45-calibre, with is grains of powder and a .bullet of 3u0 grains. blr, Roosevelt believes that we will even adopt a smaller calibre-one of .25G to .310-with 40 grains of powder, and a 200-grain bullet, But then the powder used to-day is a stronger substance than it was in former days. After all, there always is the personal equation which does the work, and so " the man behind the gun counts most."

It represents a marshy stretch, with a bit of water in the foreground, and here and there along the horizon is a glint of red, as the sun  out through the in  clouds. It is quiet, , and thoroughly the work of a close student of nature. Nven more sympathetic than this is, perhaps, one of the best Rousseaus ever seen in this country. It is willed "Edge of the Woods." The theme is a simple one; there are  trees, that al.. ways appeal very strongly to this painter; an Autumn sky , with  cloud effect, cool, tender, and . The difficult problem of blue, always a stumbling  to the painter, Rousseau has overcome, a? was his wont, with  and apparently, no effort. The rich tones of reddish greens, of tender yellows, of distant haze-all these he has caught with the feeling of a poet,  con amore. There are four more  by Rousseau, ono of which, " Land scape," (No. 8,) is also a worthy example, though somewhat less important. Here is a hillside, near hfs favorite Font0.tne bleau, covered with shrubbery, with rocks in the foreground. It is very simple, but the artist has invested the scene with his personal touch, which,  a magician s wand, seems to transform  ything it comes near.  The clever Eugene Fromentin is repre sented by two of his Oriental              op Arabs on horses, one called " The Fal coner," and the other " A Fantasia," dexter. ous, dainty in technique, monstrously habits in handling, gray in color, full of action, vim, and snap, and-not too Profound. He seems to get all the qualities for which he is Famous in his moderate-sized panels, and when !t comes to the larger canvases, it is only after all an  of his smaller work. Thus in his " Falconer " thero is the facility of brush work on gar ment, f0.ce, sky, anti foreground, while in his larger " Fantasia " the same  peated by the addition of several more fig. uses.

abstract: Among the changes proposed, of which just complaint is made, are those which are intended to discourage and hinder third panty and independent nomina tions. Under a proposed amendment it must have cast 20,000 in the State, and no  provision is made for local nominations at all.
